03818nam a22004575i 9780228002260DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280022607 a10.1515/97802280022602doi  a(DE-B1597)657948  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLA412.B42 7aEDU0360002bisacsh04a3712231 aBennett, Paul W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe State of the System :bA Reality Check on Canada's Schools /cPaul W. Bennett. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b10 photos, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tA School System under Stress -- tShaping of the System -- tTesting Time -- tConsolidate and Control -- tEducation on Wheels -- tPublic Choice in the System -- tThe “One-Size-Fits-All” Model -- tThe “Success for All” Curriculum -- tStudent Assessment Experiments -- tThe Big Disconnect -- tThe School Closure Wars -- tSchool Boards in Crisis -- tEpilogue: Re-engineering Education- Flip the System and Build from the Schools Up -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the last fifty years, Canada's public schools have been absorbed into a modern education system that functions much like Max Weber's infamous iron cage. Crying out for democratic school-level reform, the system is now a centralized, bureaucratic fortress that, every year, becomes softer on standards for students, less accessible to parents, further out of touch with communities, and surprisingly unresponsive to classroom teachers. Exploring the nature of the Canadian education order in all its dimensions, The State of the System explains how public schools came to be so bureaucratic, confronts the critical issues facing kindergarten to grade 12 public schools in all ten provinces, and addresses the need for systemic reform. Going beyond a diagnosis of the stresses, strains, and ills present in the system, Paul Bennett proposes a bold plan to re-engineer schools on a more human scale as the first step in truly reforming public education. In place of school consolidation and managerialism, one-size-fits-all uniformity, limited school choice, and the "success-for-all" curriculum, Bennett advocates for a new set of priorities: decentralize school governance, deprogram education ministries and school districts, listen to parents and teachers, and revitalize local education democracy. Tackling the thorny issues besetting contemporary school systems in Canada, The State of the System issues a clarion call for more responsive, engaged, and accountable public schools.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducationzCanadaxEvaluation. 7aEDUCATION / Organizations & Institutions.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228002260?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228002260423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228002260/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles